  "5 years": "",
  "76 years": "",
  "200 years": "",
  "12 years": "",
  "Halley's Comet returns to the inner solar system approximately every 75-76 years; it last appeared in 1986.": "",
  "Comets typically have two tails. What are they?": "",
  "A dust tail and an ion (gas) tail": "",
  "A visible tail and an invisible tail": "",
  "A magnetic tail and a gravity tail": "",
  "A fire tail and an ice tail": "",
  "The dust tail is curved (pushed by radiation pressure) and the ion tail is straight (pushed by solar wind along magnetic field lines).": "",
  "What is a 'comet nucleus'?": "",
  "The bright glow around a comet": "",
  "The tail of a comet": "",
  "A comet's orbit": "",
  "The solid, central part of a comet made of ice, dust, and rock": "",
  "The nucleus is the solid body of a comet, typically a few km across, composed of frozen gases, dust, and rock.": "",
  "What is a 'coma'?": "",
  "A prolonged state of deep unconsciousness caused by severe brain injury, metabolic disruption, or toxic substance exposure": "",
  "A cooler, magnetically active area on the Sun's photosphere that appears dark compared to the surrounding brighter regions": "",
  "The fuzzy, glowing cloud of gas and dust surrounding a comet's nucleus": "",
  "The elongated stream of ionized gas and dust particles extending millions of kilometers behind a comet near the Sun": "",
  "As a comet approaches the Sun, heat vaporizes surface ices, creating the coma — a diffuse cloud around the nucleus.": "",
  "What is a 'meteoroid'?": "",
  "A fragment of lunar surface material ejected into space by a large impact event on the Moon's cratered highlands or maria": "",
  "A rocky body orbiting the Sun between Mars and Jupiter, ranging from boulder-sized fragments to objects hundreds of km across": "",
  "A small rock or particle in space, before it enters Earth's atmosphere": "",
  "A piece of cosmic debris that has survived its fiery passage through Earth's atmosphere and impacted the planet's surface": "",
  "A meteoroid is defined as a small body (from dust-grain to ~1 m) traveling through space.": "",
  "What is the 'Oort Cloud'?": "",
  "A luminous cloud of gas and dust particles drifting through the Jovian system, illuminated by reflected sunlight from Jupiter": "",
  "An atmospheric formation of water ice or carbon dioxide crystals suspended high above the Martian surface during cold seasons": "",
  "A hypothetical spherical shell of icy bodies surrounding the solar system at ~50,000 AU": "",
  "An interstellar cloud of ionized hydrogen gas and cosmic dust, illuminated by radiation from nearby hot young stellar objects": "",
  "The Oort Cloud is theorized to contain trillions of icy objects at the outermost boundary of the Sun's gravitational influence.": "",
  "What is 'sublimation' in comet science?": "",
  "The rapid oxidation and burning of cometary material as it heats up from friction with atmospheric molecules during reentry": "",
  "The phase transition where gaseous molecules lose thermal energy and solidify directly into crystalline ice at low temperatures": "",
  "The transition of ice directly to gas without passing through a liquid phase": "",
  "The phase transition where solid ice absorbs thermal energy and changes into liquid water at temperatures above the freezing point": "",
  "In the vacuum of space, comet ices sublimate (go directly from solid to gas) when heated by the Sun, forming the coma and tails.": "",
  "What is a 'bolide'?": "",
  "An extremely bright meteor, often exploding in the atmosphere (fireball)": "",
  "An explosive release of magma, gas, and rocky debris from a volcanic vent on the surface of a geologically active planetary moon": "",
  "A broken piece of a cometary nucleus that separated from the main body due to tidal forces or thermal stress near the Sun": "",
  "A rocky or metallic body orbiting the Sun in the inner solar system, left over from the earliest stages of planetary formation": "",
  "A bolide is a very bright fireball meteor, sometimes producing sonic booms and fragmenting explosively.": "",
  "What is a 'meteor shower radiant'?": "",
  "The point in the sky from which shower meteors appear to originate": "",
  "The brightest meteor in a shower": "",
  "The comet that causes the shower": "",
  "The time of peak activity": "",
  "Due to perspective, parallel meteor trails seem to radiate from one point — the radiant. Showers are named for the constellation containing this point.": "",
  "What is 'outgassing' in comets?": "",
  "The release of gas from a comet's nucleus as ices sublimate near the Sun": "",
  "The exhaust from a rocket": "",
  "Gas trapped inside meteorites": "",
  "Gas produced by a comet's engine": "",
  "Outgassing produces jets of gas from a comet's nucleus, driving the formation of the coma and tails.": "",
  "What is 'perihelion' for a comet?": "",
  "The comet's birthplace": "",
  "The farthest point from the Sun": "",
  "The point in its orbit closest to the Sun, where comets are most active": "",
  "When a comet splits apart": "",
  "At perihelion, a comet receives maximum solar heating, producing the most spectacular coma and tail.": "",
  "What is a 'sungrazing comet'?": "",
  "A comet made of solar material": "",
  "A comet that orbits inside Mercury": "",
  "A comet that passes extremely close to the Sun, sometimes within the corona": "",
  "A comet that hits the Sun": "",
  "Sungrazing comets pass within a few solar radii of the Sun; many disintegrate due to extreme heat and tidal forces.": "",
  "You observe a comet in the evening sky with its tail pointing upward (away from the horizon where the Sun set). Why does the tail point this way?": "",
  "Earth's gravitational field exerts a measurable attractive force on the comet's gas and dust tail, drawing it toward our planet": "",
  "Atmospheric wind currents on Earth interact with the comet's tail material, pushing it into an upward-pointing orientation": "",
  "The tail always points away from the Sun, so after sunset it points upward/away from the Sun below the horizon": "",
  "The comet's orbital trajectory carries it on an upward path relative to the observer, dragging its tail along behind it": "",
  "Solar radiation and wind always push comet tails anti-sunward, so the tail points away from the direction of the Sun.": "",
  "In February 2013, a ~20-meter asteroid exploded over Chelyabinsk, Russia, injuring over 1,500 people. Why wasn't it detected in advance?": "",
  "The asteroid materialized in near-Earth space overnight with no prior orbital history, giving telescopes zero warning time for detection": "",
  "It approached from the Sun's direction, making it invisible to ground-based surveys": "",
  "The asteroid's extreme distance from Earth throughout its approach kept it well below the detection threshold of all survey telescopes": "",
  "Russia lacked any operational astronomical survey telescopes capable of detecting and tracking incoming near-Earth asteroid threats": "",
  "The Chelyabinsk meteor came from the Sun's direction, where the Sun's glare prevents detection — a known blind spot.": "",
  "A comet is observed to have a straight, blue ion tail and a broader, curved yellowish dust tail. What causes the difference?": "",
  "The yellowish color originates from sulfur compounds vaporized from the comet's nucleus and excited by ultraviolet solar radiation": "",
  "The blue ion tail acts as a reflective surface that mirrors the color of the surrounding sky background and scattered sunlight": "",
  "A significant temperature difference between the two tails causes them to emit different wavelengths of thermal blackbody radiation": "",
  "The ion tail is pushed by solar wind (straight); the dust tail is pushed by radiation pressure and curves due to orbital motion": "",
  "Solar wind pushes ions straight back at high speed; heavier dust particles lag behind, curving with the comet's orbital motion.": "",
  "65 million years ago, an asteroid impact contributed to the extinction of the dinosaurs. What evidence supports this?": "",
  "A worldwide layer of iridium (rare on Earth, common in asteroids) at the K-Pg boundary, plus the Chicxulub crater": "",
  "Volcanic activity on Earth reached a dramatic peak during that geological period, releasing massive amounts of toxic gas and ash": "",
  "Fossilized dinosaur bones discovered worldwide display characteristic thermal burn marks consistent with exposure to extreme heat": "",
  "A contemporaneous impact crater of similar size has been identified on the lunar surface, suggesting a linked double-impact event": "",
  "The iridium anomaly and the 180-km Chicxulub crater in Mexico provide strong evidence for the impact hypothesis.": "",
